THE NEXT GENERATION OF INDICATORS FOR PARTICULATE MATTER WILL
REQUIRE CITIZEN ENGAGEMENT, TAILORED MONITORING TO ACCOUNT
FOR REGIONAL DIFFERENCES, AND CITIZEN ENGAGEMENT.
ENABLE BETTER USE OF SATELLITE DATA.
Conduct targeted campaigns to enable better use of
satellite data and improve models where networks are not possible. Countries at the lowest level
of development are unlikely to have the institutional capacity, financial resources, or politica will to
sustain a ground-based monitoring program. Satellite data can be a surrogate with appropriate
validation with ground data. Short (e.g., 1-year) campaigns to find stop-gap data from satellite and
meterology data would improve application of satellite data and models for ongoing
understanding of air quality in a country.
Expand and improve a set of multi-pollutant,
multi-purpose indicators to compare monitoring data across countries. New and improved indicators should be
developed that aim to emphasize the health and economic benefits of good air quality, not only for PM but also for
all air pollutants. Indicators that include estimates for anthropogenic and transported pollution are particularly
. Develop new personal sensors that link to social media as citizen science. The growth of
mobile phones, the Internet, and social media has greatly changed the global information landscape. Air quality
monitoring could leverage this but requires the development of smaller monitors or similar surrogates (e.g.,
visibility via photographs) plus the quality assurance processes and electronic tools and motivations for people to
contribute the data as ctiizens participating in open science.
TAILORED MONITORING. PM sources, concentrations, and composition vary by region and country, as does the
institutional capacity to support air quality monitoring. Therefore, the next generation air quality monitors,
supporting systems, and indicators should consider a country’s priorities and cpacity when developing
ground-based monitor networks, institutional arrangements for monitor operation, application of satellite and
modeled information, and stakeholder communications. Then, even with differences in regulations and
